text: USS Cole DD-155 photographed from USS Philadelphia CL-41 just before the Operation Torch Landings - November 1942  In the early morning hours of November 8, 1942, the two WW1 era Wickes-class destroyers USS Bernadou & USS Cole penetrated the harbor of Safi Morocco with the intention of landing troops to prevent Vichy French sabotage of the critical port infrastructure.  USS Cole landed 175 Soldiers of the 47th Infantry under fire on a pier at Safi. Despite Vichy French resistance, only ten US Army Personnel were killed and the mission was considered a success.  USS Cole was modified for this mission by having her mast removed, the ship received the Presidential Unit Citation for her performance in Operation Torch.  A Wickes-class destroyer launched in 1919, USS Cole was named for Edward B. Cole, a USMC officer who died as a result of the wounds he received at the Battle of Belleau Wood in WW1. In addition to the Presidential Unit Citation, USS Cole received three battle stars for her WW2 service, survived WW2, and was sold for scrap October 1947.  #warships #navy

text: Moroccan Culinary Extravaganza - Chicken Tagine with Apricots and Almonds  Introduction:Embark on a flavorful journey to Morocco with Chicken Tagine, a dish that reflects the aromatic and vibrant spices of Moroccan cuisine. This tagine, featuring tender chicken, sweet apricots, and crunchy almonds, captures the essence of the rich culinary traditions of North Africa. Join us as we guide you through creating this Moroccan culinary masterpiece, allowing you to experience the harmony of sweet and savory flavors in every bite. Ingredients: For the Marinade:  1.5 pounds bone-in, skin-on chicken thighs 1 tablespoon ground cumin  1 tablespoon ground coriander 1 tablespoon smoked paprika 1 teaspoon ground cinnamon Salt and black pepper to taste 2 tablespoons olive oil For the Tagine: 1 large onion, thinly sliced 3 cloves garlic, minced  1 tablespoon grated fresh ginger 1/2 cup dried apricots, halved 1/2 cup whole blanched almonds 1 cup chicken broth 2 tablespoons honey 1 tablespoon preserved lemon peel, chopped (or substitute with lemon zest) Fresh cilantro or parsley for garnish Cooked couscous for serving

Given the Republic of Djibouti's substantial advancements in port facilities and free zones since 2017, including the ongoing construction of the Damerjog oil terminal (DL.BP) expected to be completed by early 2024, there is a pressing need to equip qualified personnel for efficient maritime operations. Notably, the Autonomous Ports of Tadjourah and Ghoubet, along with the operational DMP, underscore the importance of training programs. These initiatives aim to prepare future merchant navy officers, deck and engineering officers, and specialized executives in the maritime domain.  To achieve this goal, providing appropriate training is crucial, fostering the skills required to manage operations within these ports and facilities. These training programs serve as a significant asset for the port community, playing a pivotal role in enhancing operational capabilities, ensuring infrastructure efficiency, and nurturing the next generation of maritime professionals.  A message conveying these objectives has been communicated to H.E. Mr. Mohamed Douhour Hersi, intending to transmit it to specialized Moroccan institutions, such as the Casablanca Maritime Academy, seeking collaboration and support in this important endeavor.

text: Zahra's shocking story unraveled in 2001, when she began experiencing acute abdominal pains at the age of 75 in Rabat, the capital of Morocco.  She was rushed to hospital wrecked in pain and stomach swollen to an unnatural size. Doctors suspected she had an ovarian tumour, but an ultrasound scan revealed only a bizarre mass that they could not identify.  In order to find out more, they sent Zahra for further scan. The doctors are shocked by what they see; inside the 75-year-old woman's stomach is a baby, and even more shockingly, the baby had been conceived 46 years ago.  Back in 1955, Zahra was a blissfully married young woman, pregnant with her first child. The 26-year-old housewife said she was very happy to be having the child although she had pains and bleeding. "The baby wanted to come," she said. after 48 hours of excruciatingly painful labour, the baby still would not come. She was rushed to the local hospital and doctors told her that if they did not operate on her, her baby would die.  Lying in a hospital bed, Zahra heard a woman screaming as she died on the operation table during a Caesarean section. Horrified, Zahra decided the risk wasn't worth it. She fled the hospital and went back to her small village outside Casablanca.  After a few days, the pain miraculously stopped. According to local legend, babies can go to sleep inside a mother's womb to protect her honour.  So Zahra thought her baby had just gone to sleep. She believed that one day, her "sleeping baby" would wake up. "I could still feel him inside me, and i thought, if he wanted to stay sleeping, I would let him stay," she said.  To forget the trauma of her failed pregnancy, she adopted three children, who grew up and went on to have children of their own  Fast foward 46 years later, Zahra's excruciating pains returns. Her adopted son becomes worried about his mother's declining health and takes her to all the local doctors, hoping to find a cure.  "I took her to doctors in Casablanca. We took her everywhere, we tried everywhere - then we hear there was this doctor in Rabat," said Bouchaib Aboutalib.  She was barely able to make the gruelling four hour journey to Rabat. Doctors performed an ultrasound and discovered that her "sleeping baby" was actually an ectopic pregnancy that had become a fetus mummified in her womb over nearly half a century.  Ectopic literally means "out of place." In a normal pregnancy, the fertilised egg travels down the fallopian tube and implants itself in the uterus. There, it is able to get as much space and nutrients that the uterus provides to grow into a healthy baby.  However, in an ectopic pregnancy, the egg implants itself in the fallopian tube. In extremely rare cases such as Zahra's, the fetus bursts out of the fallopian tube and then goes on to develop in the abdominal cavity.  Nine months into the pregnancy, the pregnancy pains Zahra began to experience were actually signs of a distressed baby as it was running out of oxygen. Zahra mistook them as signs that she was ready to give birth. In reality, the baby would never have been able to come out naturally through her cervix.  In 1955, she would have required a complicated procedure to remove the baby. Her fleeing the hospital 46 years ago might have saved her life, as there was a small chance that the technology available in those days was advanced enough to separate the fetus from her vital organs.  Even in 2001, the operation was a difficult one. The danger was that she would bleed to death as they removed the calcified stone baby. The baby had fused to Zahra's bladder, stomach, abdominal wall and veins.  Any minor slip of the scapel could have punctured these organs and cost Zahra her life.  It surgeons almost four hours to remove the fetus from its tomb.  The fetus weighed seven pounds and measured 42cm in length. At the time of the documentary, only 300 cases of such stone babies, also known as lithopedions, had been reported in medical history.

text: The Western Sahara, a vast expanse of desert bordering Morocco, Algeria, Mauritania, and the Atlantic Ocean, has been embroiled in a complex and protracted conflict since the 1970s. This post delves into the historical roots of the dispute, the key players involved, the ongoing challenges, and the uncertain prospects for a lasting resolution.  Contested Origins:  The Western Sahara's status has been a subject of contention since Spain's withdrawal as the colonial power in 1975. Morocco claims the territory as an integral part of its kingdom, citing historical and cultural ties. The Polisario Front, an independence movement representing the Sahrawi people, vehemently opposes this claim, advocating for the establishment of a sovereign Sahrawi Arab Democratic Republic (SADR).  Fueling the Flames:  The conflict erupted in 1975 when Morocco annexed the northern two-thirds of the territory while Mauritania occupied the southern third. The Polisario Front launched a guerilla war against both Moroccan and Mauritanian forces, employing hit-and-run tactics and ambushes. In 1979, Mauritania withdrew from the conflict, ceding its occupied territory to Morocco.  The Fortification Wall and Stalemate:  To consolidate its control, Morocco constructed a massive sand berm, stretching over 2,700 kilometers, effectively dividing the territory and hindering the Polisario Front's movements. This wall, along with a heavily fortified buffer zone, has resulted in a military stalemate for decades.  Key Players:  Morocco: Backed by France and other allies, Morocco maintains a strong military presence in Western Sahara and invests heavily in developing the region's infrastructure and economy.  Polisario Front: Supported by Algeria and a handful of other countries, the Polisario Front operates largely in exile and relies on international diplomatic efforts to advance its cause.  Algeria: Algeria provides the Polisario Front with safe haven, training, and logistical support, viewing Morocco's claim on Western Sahara as a threat to its own territorial integrity.  United Nations: The United Nations has been involved in mediating the conflict since the early 1970s, but efforts to find a lasting solution have so far been unsuccessful.  Humanitarian Concerns:  The conflict has had a devastating impact on the Sahrawi people. Thousands have been displaced, living in refugee camps in Algeria or facing limited opportunities and restricted freedoms within Moroccan-controlled areas. Concerns persist regarding human rights abuses, resource exploitation, and the psychological trauma inflicted by years of uncertainty and conflict.  Prospects for Peace:  The future of Western Sahara remains uncertain. Despite numerous UN-led peace talks and diplomatic initiatives, no concrete solution has been reached. Morocco's insistence on autonomy within its sovereignty and the Polisario Front's unwavering commitment to self-determination create an seemingly unbridgeable gap.
name: Barron West
